The South African bond market extended its rally at lunchtime on Tuesday, with the yield on the benchmark R186 touching its lowest level in more than four months. The rally in the bond market coincided with better than expected inflation data and as the rand continued its march higher, hitting the R13 to the dollar mark for the first time since 2015.Consumer price inflation slowed to an annual rate of 6.6% in January, from 6.8% in December, an outcome that favours the bond market."The sharper than expected decline in South African inflation particularly core inflation last month supports our view that the country s monetary tightening cycle is now over," said John Ashbourne, Africa economist at Capital Economics in a note.The yield on the benchmark R186 bond flattened to 8.57%, its lowest level since October, from 8.61%.The US treasury bonds, meanwhile, tracked weaker after US Federal Reserve chairperson Janet Yellen signalled the Fed s intention to raise interest rates, possibly in March.The US 10-year treasury note yielded 2.4735%, 2.4322% previously.